2026-06-21 | Lexicographically Smallest String After One Global Character Swap

	Question
Return the lexicographically smallest string obtainable.
	Key Insight
To make the string lexicographically smaller, we should improve the earliest possible position.
For each character s[i]:
•	Check whether there exists a smaller character that appears somewhere later in the string.
•	If yes, swapping those two characters globally will make the first differing position smaller, which is always optimal.
So:
1. Find the first position where a beneficial swap exists.
2. Swap that character with the smallest possible character appearing later.
3. Perform the swap globally.
	Example
	s = "ccad"
	At index 0:
			'c'
	A smaller character exists later:
			'a'
	Swap all 'c' and 'a'
	Result:
			aacd
	Approach
1. Store the last occurrence of every character.
2. Traverse the string from left to right.
3. For current character s[i]:
		try all smaller characters
		from 'a' to s[i]-1
4. If a smaller character exists later:
		perform a global swap
		and return the result.
5. If no beneficial swap exists,
		return the original string.
	Time Complexity
	O(26 × n)
	Space Complexity
	O(26)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    string chooseandswap(string s) {
        vector<int> last(26, -1);
        for(int i = 0; i < s.size(); i++) {
            last[s[i] - 'a'] = i;
        }
        for(int i = 0; i < s.size(); i++) {
            int cur = s[i] - 'a';
            for(int ch = 0; ch < cur; ch++) {
                if(last[ch] > i) {
                    char a = s[i];
                    char b = char(ch + 'a');
                    for(char &c : s) {
                        if(c == a)
                            c = b;
                        else if(c == b)
                            c = a;
                    }
                    return s;
                }
            }
        }
        return s;
    }
};
	Key Insight
The lexicographical order is determined by the earliest differing position. Therefore, the optimal strategy is to find the first character that can be replaced by a smaller character appearing later in the string and perform that global swap immediately. This guarantees the smallest possible resulting string.
